\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Development-0h55"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the flow from the ends of the five glass tubes 55 minutes after ink
 was introduced.
 The patterns shows that the bottom of the shallowest tube ends in the unsaturat
ed zone while that of the second tube ends at the top of the full capillary
 zone.
 The flow in the full capillary zone is as fast as around the line AB, while
 that in the unsaturated zone is much less, lower the lower the saturation.
 The spot made by the shallowest tube is also less dark due to the presence
 of air in the unsaturated zone.The thickness of the full capillary zone
 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 also gives us an indication about the size of the sand grains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\pi r\tau\approx\pi r^{2}\rho gh
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\approx\frac{2}{r}\frac{\tau}{\rho g}\rightarrow r\approx\frac{2}{h}\frac{\tau}{\rho g}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\approx75\times10^{-3}N/m$
\end_inset

 surface trension of water, which is sufficiently accurate due to the fact
 that the angle of the water surface and the grains is generally small,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho g\approx10^{4}N/m^{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\approx0.04m$
\end_inset

.
 With this, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\approx\frac{2}{0.04}\frac{75\times10^{-3}}{10^{4}}=0.000375m\approx0.4mm
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 being the radius of an equivalent glass tube in which the suction height
 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is computed.
 The diameter of equivalent glass grains with around 35% porosity would
 be around 10 times this size, i.e.
 around 4 mm.
 This indeed, implies that Pennink used very coarse sand to very find gravel,
 as one may already have guessed given the visible grains in the Photo.
 The hydraulic conductivity of the medium in Penninks laboratory model is,
 therefore, much higher than that of fine dune sand of around 8-10 m/d.
 We will determine the conductivity of the laboratory model later one from
 modelling Pennink's experiments.
\end_layout

