\begin_layout Section
Upward flow below extraction canals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pennink's book thus starts with field observations which he used to verify
 the the laboratory experiments with his physical cross sectional model,
 which had just shown that flow lines near an extraction canal point upward.
 Pennink had three series of 5 to 5 small piezometers installed vertically
 1 to 1.5 m apart, at 0, 5, 10 and 15 m from the center line of 4 m wide
 extracting canal.
 A rather impervious clay layer prevented vertical flow at about 8 below
 the canal stage.
 This setup of 19 piezometers allowed mapping the spatial head distribution
 near the canal with great accuracy.
 Pennink used these measurements to draw lines of equal head in the cross
 section and also drow streamlines more or less perpendicular to them.
 This way, the upward flow near the canal, due to contracting streamlines,
 was demonstrated to exist in the field as it did in the laboratory model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is tempting with the tools of today, to regenerate the flow field that
 Pennink came up with.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
